@node "features" "What does it do?"

   IFF to WAV is an easy to use batch converter.  It will
   convert any standard IFF/8svx Amiga sound sample to a
   standard PC 8bit RIFF/WAV sound sample.

   Mono IFF samples are converted to mono WAV samples, and
   stereo IFF samples are converted to stereo WAV samples.

   The program can be run from the Workbench or from the CLI.
   But there are no arguments or options so there is really
   not much point in running it from the Shell...

   Why do so many programs want to start with arguments, anyway?
   Can't they get along with each other?

   -------------------------------------------------------------

   Oh, I almost forgot - it's fashionable to brag that a program
   doesn't cause any Enforcer hits.

   So: 

        *** This program causes no Enforcer hits! ***


   Actually, the truth is that no program should ever cause 
   an Enforcer hit.
@endnode

@node "requirements" "What do I need?"

  This program requires at least v2.xx of the OS

  You will also need enough free ram for the
  sample conversion buffers.

  The buffers are dynamically sized to fit each sample
  as it is being converted so unless you are trying to 
  convert really huge samples, there won't be a problem.

  If there isn't enough free ram available, the program
  will politely let you know.

  You will also need the standard ASL.library (which is
  part of the WB 2.xx and 3.xx) so there won't be a
  problem with that either, unless you have removed it
  for some reason...


  ------------------------------------------------------


  Recommended but not required:

  KingCon: A handy replacement for the standard Console
           windows.  It allows you to scroll back to see
           stuff that has scrolled off the top of the
           window, send the window contents to a file or
           your printer, and many other features.


  ReqTools (and the ReqTools patch): Replacement for the
           standard ASL requesters.  Gives you several
           enhancements over the ASL requesters and also
           has a prefs program where you can set your own
           sizes and locations for the various requesters.



  You'll find both of these on Aminet.
@endnode

@node "install" "Where can I stick it?"

 Installation is simply a matter of dropping the
 IFF to WAV program wherever you want.

 It is OK to change the name of IFFtoWAV
@endnode

@node "use" "What do I do with it?"


  OK, the program is actually pretty self-explanatory, so
  no one will ever read this.  But just in case:

  When you start the program, you will get a standard
  Console window for the output, and an ASL (or ReqTools)
  file requester where you can select one or more IFF samples
  to be converted to WAV samples.

  When you are ready, click the "Ready" gadget   ;)

  Now you will get an ASL path requester where you can set
  the path you want the converted samples saved to.  You can
  create a new directory if you wish by typing in it's name
  in the requester.

  Again, click "Ready" whenever you are ready...

  Now each IFF sample will be converted to a WAV sample, and
  saved into the selected directory.  The console window will
  keep you informed of the progress, and let you know about
  any problems.

  Mono IFF samples are converted to mono 8bit WAV samples, and
  stereo IFF samples are converted to stereo 8bit WAV samples.

  Large samples can take a few seconds to convert, especially
  stereo samples, so don't be alarmed if you are converting a
  3meg sample and nothing seems to be happening...

  Once all samples have been converted, you'll get the file
  requester again, asking for more samples to be converted.
  If you want to quit, click on the "Quit" or "Cancel" button,
  or select more samples to continue.
 
  That's all there is to it.

  If you have any questions or problems, or just want to say
  "thanks" for the program, write @{" me " link "contact" 0}
@endnode

